the process, political transition, economic policy, economic results (GDP development, inflation, unemployment), changes in outside indicators (balance of payments), privatization, transformation of the financial sector, and changes in the business sector and institutional development. The book also compares Czech development in this transformative era to those of Poland and Hungary. As in Hungary and Poland, the Czech Republic underwent an exceptional qualitative shift from a system centrally planned to one that was market-based. The book concludes that despite mistakes and hardships, the overall transformation process in Central Europe has been successful.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aBanks and bankingxHistoryx20th centuryxCzech Republic. 0aBanks and bankingzCzech RepublicxHistoryy20th century. 0aBanks and banking. 0aBusiness enterprisesxHistoryx20th centuryxCzech Republic. 0aBusiness enterpriseszCzech RepublicxHistoryy20th century. 0aBusiness enterprises. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / Economics.2bisacsh  aBanks, Political economy, Transition economies, Central and Eastern Europe, Postcommunism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2017z978311078143440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633861806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633861806/original  a978-3-11-078143-4  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK